Patch Set 1:

> because of QRect::center() not having the expected value after calling QRect::moveCenter().

Many usages of QRect::moveCenter() look as follows rect.moveCenter(anotherRect.center());

Patch Set 2:

Another reason is that if you don't want the lifetime tracking, you can always (well, since C++11) use the classical

    static T &instance() {
        static T self;
        return self;
    }

pattern. Q_G_S, OTOH, is probably used for two reasons:

- it was used in pre-C++11 code and people just didn't feel the need to port away from it
- it's isDestroyed() or exists() methods are actively used

That means that, by now, the raison d'etre of Q_GLOBAL_STATIC is its lifetime tracking. The code path that didn't rely on C++11 thread-safe function-level statics is completely gone.

To me, it seems counter-productive to diminish that crucial one difference to built-in statics by being laissez-faire with the implementation.
